The [Namcha Barwa Himal](/Namcha_Barwa_Himal), an imposing eastern segment of the vast [Himalayas](/Himalayas), as observed from the orbital vantage point of [Apollo 9](/Apollo_9), offers a stark reminder of Earth's colossal geological features.

A mountain range, or its less dramatic cousin, a hill range, is fundamentally a linear arrangement of interconnected [mountains](/Mountain) or [hills](/Hill), bound together by elevated terrain. It’s a concept that sounds simple enough, yet the scale and complexity involved are anything but. When these individual ranges, sharing commonalities in their form, underlying structure, and general alignment, coalesce due to a shared geological genesis—typically an [orogeny](/Orogeny), or mountain-building event—they are then classified as a mountain system or a broader mountain belt. Most of the truly significant mountain ranges gracing Earth's surface, the ones that reshape continents and dictate climates, are the direct, often violent, outcome of the relentless dance of [plate tectonics](/Plate_tectonics). This isn't a unique terrestrial phenomenon; similar linear elevations, often dubbed "Montes," have been observed on numerous planetary mass objects throughout our [Solar System](/Solar_System) and are widely expected to be a common topographical feature across most [terrestrial planets](/Terrestrial_planet).

These colossal geological formations are rarely unbroken. They are typically segmented and sculpted by intervening [highlands](/Highland), naturally occurring [mountain passes](/Mountain_pass) that offer routes through their formidable barriers, and the ubiquitous carving action of [valleys](/Valley). It’s worth noting that the individual peaks composing a single mountain range are not necessarily uniform in their fundamental [geologic structure](/Structural_geology) or their [petrology](/Petrology)—the study of their rock compositions. Instead, they frequently represent a complex tapestry woven from diverse orogenic expressions and distinct [terranes](/Terrane). This can manifest as an intricate mix of geological features, including massive [thrust sheets](/Thrust_fault) where rock layers are pushed over one another, dramatic [uplifted blocks](/Fault-block_mountain) that rise along fault lines, elegantly contorted [fold](/Fold_(geology)) mountains, and the often volatile contributions of [volcanic](/Volcanic) landforms, all combining to produce an astonishing variety of [rock types](/Lithology) within a seemingly cohesive range.

### Major ranges

One might expect the planet to organize its grandest features with some predictability, and in this, it largely obliges. Most of Earth's geologically youthful and most prominent mountain ranges on the land surface are neatly associated with one of two primary tectonic systems: the dynamic [Pacific Ring of Fire](/Pacific_Ring_of_Fire) or the expansive [Alpide belt](/Alpide_belt).

The [Pacific Ring of Fire](/Pacific_Ring_of_Fire) traces a horseshoe-shaped path around the vast [Pacific Ocean](/Pacific_Ocean), a notorious zone of intense seismic and volcanic activity. Its terrestrial mountain components include the majestic [Andes](/Andes) of South America, which then extend northward through the complex geological labyrinth of the [North American Cordillera](/North_American_Cordillera). From there, the chain continues across the frigid reaches of the [Aleutian Range](/Aleutian_Range), then arcs westward through the volcanic landscapes of the [Kamchatka Peninsula](/Kamchatka), the island nation of [Japan](/Japan), portions of [China](/China), the archipelagic nation of the [Philippines](/Philippines), the wild terrains of [Papua New Guinea](/Papua_New_Guinea), ultimately reaching the shores of [New Zealand](/New_Zealand). The [Andes](/Andes) themselves, stretching an impressive 7,000 kilometres (approximately 4,350 miles) along the western edge of South America, are frequently cited as the world's longest continuous mountain system on a continental landmass.

Meanwhile, the [Alpide belt](/Alpide_belt) presents an equally formidable, if geographically distinct, series of ranges. This immense system, a product of the collision between the [African](/Africa), [Arabian](/Arabian_Plate), and [Indian](/Indian_Plate) plates with the [Eurasian Plate](/Eurasian_Plate), spans an astonishing 15,000 kilometres (about 9,300 miles) across southern [Eurasia](/Eurasia). Its vast reach extends from the islands of [Java](/Java) within Maritime [Southeast Asia](/Southeast_Asia) all the way to the [Iberian Peninsula](/Iberian_Peninsula) at the westernmost fringes of [Western Europe](/Western_Europe). This belt encompasses some of the most iconic and geologically active mountain ranges on the planet, including the towering [Himalayas](/Himalayas), the rugged [Karakoram](/Karakoram), the formidable [Hindu Kush](/Hindu_Kush), the dramatic [Alborz](/Alborz) range, the imposing [Caucasus Mountains](/Caucasus_Mountains), and the classic [Alps](/Alps). Within the heart of the [Himalayas](/Himalayas) lies the ultimate terrestrial peak, [Mount Everest](/Mount_Everest), whose summit reaches an elevation of 8,848 metres (29,029 feet) above sea level, a testament to the immense forces that shaped this region.

Beyond these two dominant global systems, numerous other significant mountain ranges carve their own paths across the continents. These include the frigid peaks of the [Arctic Cordillera](/Arctic_Cordillera), the ancient, weathered contours of the [Appalachian Mountains](/Appalachian_Mountains) in eastern North America, the extensive [Great Dividing Range](/Great_Dividing_Range) of eastern Australia, the remote and rugged [East Siberian Mountains](/East_Siberian_Mountains), the vast [Altai Mountains](/Altai_Mountains) of Central Asia, the picturesque [Scandinavian Mountains](/Scandinavian_Mountains), the historically significant [Qinling](/Qinling) range in China, the lush [Western Ghats](/Western_Ghats) and the venerable [Vindhya Range](/Vindhya_Range) in India, the desolate [Byrranga Mountains](/Byrranga_Mountains) in northern Siberia, and the verdant [Annamite Range](/Annamite_Range) of Indochina. However, if one broadens the definition of a mountain range to encompass the vast, submerged geological features of the ocean floor, then the [Ocean Ridge](/Ocean_Ridge) unequivocally claims the title of the longest continuous mountain system on Earth, a sprawling, largely unseen chain extending for an incredible 65,000 kilometres (approximately 40,400 miles) across the globe's oceanic basins. It’s a humbling reminder that most of Earth's drama unfolds beneath the waves, far from human observation.

### Climate

The sheer presence of mountain ranges exerts a profound and often dramatic influence on regional and even global climates, fundamentally altering patterns of [rain](/Rain) and [snow](/Snow) distribution. This is not some subtle atmospheric nuance; it’s a direct consequence of basic physics. When moisture-laden air masses encounter a mountain range, they are forced to ascend its slopes. As the air rises, it cools, leading to condensation and the formation of clouds. This process invariably results in what is known as [orographic](/Orography) precipitation, manifesting as either rain or snow on the windward side of the mountains. The higher and more extensive the range, the more pronounced this effect becomes, often creating fertile, well-watered environments on one side.

Conversely, as this now-drier air descends the leeward side of the range, it warms significantly due to compression (a process described by the [adiabatic lapse rate](/Adiabatic_lapse_rate)). Critically, having shed much of its moisture on the windward slopes, this descending air is remarkably dry. The inevitable consequence is the formation of a [rain shadow](/Rain_shadow), which frequently renders the leeward side of the range arid or semi-arid, often resulting in deserts or dry steppes. A prime example of this dramatic climatic compartmentalization is seen in the [Andes](/Andes), the longest mountain range on the surface of the Earth. Its imposing presence creates a stark division of [South America](/South_America) into vastly distinct [climate regions](/Climate_regions), from the lush Amazon basin to the east to the arid Atacama Desert to the west. Mountains, it seems, are not merely geological features; they are silent arbiters of life and desolation.

### Erosion

Mountains, for all their apparent permanence, are locked in a relentless, slow-motion battle against the pervasive forces of [erosion](/Erosion) that ceaselessly work to dismantle them. This isn't a sudden cataclysm, but a patient, inexorable grinding down over geological timescales. The material stripped away from an eroding mountain range doesn't simply vanish; it is transported and deposited into adjacent [basins](/Sedimentary_basin). Over vast periods, these accumulated sediments are buried, compacted, and eventually lithified, transforming into new layers of [sedimentary rock](/Sedimentary_rock). This cycle of uplift and erosion continues in a dynamic equilibrium, with the mountains being built up even as they are simultaneously worn down, until, given enough time, they are ultimately reduced to mere low hills or expansive plains.

Consider the early [Cenozoic](/Cenozoic) uplift of the [Rocky Mountains](/Rocky_Mountains) in [Colorado](/Colorado) as a compelling case study. As this monumental uplift was underway, an estimated 10,000 feet (approximately 3,000 metres) of predominantly [Mesozoic](/Mesozoic) sedimentary [strata](/Stratum) were systematically removed by erosional processes from the core of the nascent mountain range. This immense volume of material was then spread eastward, forming vast blankets of sand and clay across the nascent [Great Plains](/Great_Plains). Crucially, this massive removal of rock occurred concurrently with the active uplift of the range. The unloading of such a substantial mass from the Earth's crust within the mountain core most likely triggered further uplift, as the region dynamically adjusted [isostatically](/Isostasy) in response to the reduction in overlying weight. It’s a testament to the Earth's deep, slow, and utterly indifferent balancing act.

Historically, [rivers](/River) have been widely considered the primary architects of mountain range erosion. Their ceaseless flow carves into bedrock, relentlessly transporting vast quantities of sediment from the highlands to the lowlands. More recent computer simulations, however, have refined this understanding, demonstrating that as mountain belts transition from periods of intense tectonic activity to more quiescent states, the overall rate of erosion tends to decrease. This reduction is attributed to a combination of factors, notably a diminished supply of abrasive particles within the riverine systems and a decrease in the frequency and scale of landslides, which are significant contributors to initial material breakdown.

### Extraterrestrial "Montes"

It’s almost quaint to think that Earth holds a monopoly on elevated linear features. Mountains, or "Montes" as they are often designated, are a common if varied, topographical element across the [Solar System](/Solar_System). While many mountains on other planets and [natural satellites](/Natural_satellite) are isolated peaks, primarily sculpted by catastrophic processes such as meteor impacts, there are indeed numerous examples of true mountain ranges displaying a linear arrangement somewhat analogous to those found on Earth, though their composition and formation mechanisms can differ dramatically.

For instance, the [Montes Apenninus](/Montes_Apenninus) on our own [Moon](/Moon) stands as a prominent lunar mountain range, though its origin is distinctly different from Earth's major ranges, having been formed by the immense impact event that created the [Imbrium Basin](/Mare_Imbrium). Further afield, [Saturn](/Saturn)'s enigmatic moon [Titan](/Titan_(moon)) and the distant [dwarf planet](/Dwarf_planet) [Pluto](/Pluto_(dwarf_planet)) both exhibit vast mountain ranges arranged in chains. However, these are not composed of silicate rock like Earth's mountains, but rather primarily of various ices—a chilling thought. Notable examples include the [Mithrim Montes](/Mithrim_Montes) and [Doom Mons](/Doom_Mons) on [Titan](/Titan_(moon)), and the aptly named [Tenzing Montes](/Tenzing_Montes) and [Hillary Montes](/Hillary_Montes) on [Pluto](/Pluto_(dwarf_planet)), named in honor of the first climbers of [Mount Everest](/Mount_Everest).

Even other [terrestrial planets](/Terrestrial_planet) in our immediate cosmic neighborhood boast their own rocky mountain ranges. [Venus](/Venus), swathed in its thick, toxic atmosphere, hosts the colossal [Maxwell Montes](/Maxwell_Montes), a mountainous region so immense it dwarfs any single mountain range found on Earth. Its formation is attributed to complex tectonic processes unique to Venus. Similarly, [Mars](/Mars) displays its own rugged topography, including the [Tartarus Montes](/Tartarus_Montes). And then there is [Jupiter](/Jupiter)'s volcanically active moon [Io](/Io_(moon)), a true geological anomaly. Its surface is dotted with numerous mountain ranges, such as the [Boösaule Montes](/Bo%C3%B6saule_Montes), Dorian, Hi'iaka, and [Euboea Montes](/Euboea_Montes), all of which are understood to have formed from intense tectonic processes driven by the enormous tidal forces exerted by its colossal parent planet. The universe, it seems, is quite fond of piling up rocks, or ice, in long, impressive lines.

